# system should be capable of tolerating faults in different parts of the system.
# Maybe an external API is changed and the API contract is invalid.
# This is why we need fault tolerance in our distributed systems. Otherwise, one small bump in any part of the system will bring the whole thing down—And surely nobody wants that. If this type of full-system crash is allowed to happen, then there is no point in building distributed systems in the first place.
# If there is something in your system not functioning as expected, you possibly have a fault.
# Distributed systems have to be able to tolerate faults so that they can continue to function even if faults appear.
# As a system owner, you should always expect faults and remain prepared accordingly. In the case of handling faults, prevention is better than cures.
# Distributed systems have to be fault tolerant by nature.

# reliability:
#  A reliable system is capable of “continuing to work correctly, even when things go wrong.
#  in a distributed system, faults are inevitable. Hardware withers away with time. Networks drop and fluctuate randomly. Power outages happen now and then. When the system is built, scenarios like these have to be kept in mind. A reliable system can operate correctly in times of such failure scenarios. The word correctly is crucial here.
#  A reliable system never continues to operate on corrupted data without any recovery effort. If this happens, the system is not reliable.
#  Hard disks are reported as having a mean time to failure (MTTF) of about 10 to 50 years. Thus, on a storage cluster with 10,000 disks, we should expect on average one disk to die per day.
#  Sometimes it will randomly cause the server program to crash and restart, such as when some null pointer dereferences due to some specific logical flow which is probably rare. Sometimes it will keep the program crashing every single time it tries to restart, maybe due to some misconfiguration in server startup parameters.

# Sometimes the bugs are not generic. You won’t encounter them until a very specific set of parameters are passed to a particular function. If you don’t know the specific set of inputs, it may be even impossible to reproduce the bug.

# In your system, as the developer, you are probably responsible for a software bug. But sometimes it can be due to some third-party library that you are using. Maybe they have some misplaced condition that caused a set of side effects which affected your system.
# A distributed system has to be reliable for its users. If a system is not reliable, its users will become increasingly skeptical about it.
# To ensure reliability, faults should be properly detected and handled.
# Both the hardware and software of a system will have faults in them—this is more or less inevitable. We can never expect things to always go right.
